Mr. SAM. HUGHES. \Vlly does the Min- ister of the Interior take this riding west of the line of the Beaver Hills lake?

Mr. OLIVER. The reason of the division being made where it is, is because of the goat area of the Beaver Hills, which are largely unoccupied on account of being rough country, and on account of the settlements around Beaver Lake having been always separated from the settlements west of the Beaver Hills. They have different connec-

tiODS, different communications, dittereut mail facilities, and so forth, and have'al- ways been directly associated with the set- tlements lying in what is included in the dis- trict of Vermilion. The Beaver Lake, in- stead of being a division of interest, has been really a sort of centre of attraction, and the settlements around the lake are re- cognized as having a community of interest, and as being divided from the settlement of Strathcona immediately west of the Beaver Hills by the wide area and the impassible barrier of these hills.

Mr. SAM. HUGHES. How wide is that area and what is the nature of the impaSv sable barrier ?

Mr. OLIVER. The Beaver Hills are a rough area extending from township 47 to township 55 from north to south and from range 1.3 to range 22 from east to west, that is to say, four townships in width by about nine townships in length. It is a rough and- wooded country. Settlement has gone in on the outskirts of it, but it is only within recent years that there has been any tratiic at all to Beaver Lake. Of recent years, owing to the exertions of the local members of Edmonton and Strathcon-a. they have been successful in getting a road directly across Beaver Hill to Beaver Lake, but that road is still in a pretty rough con- dition and passes through at least twelve miles of practically unsettled country, so that there is a very well deﬁned division between the interests on the west side of the hill and on the east.
